King Parrot Creek:

River level rises are occurring along the King Parrot Creek.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for downstream of Lake Glenmaggie.

In the 24 hours to 09:00 am today, up to 150 mm of rainfall has been recorded across the Macalister River catchment, causing rapid river level rises.

Further rainfall is forecast throughout Wednesday and Thursday, with a further 60-90 mm possible. This situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Southern Rural Water's planned releases from Lake Glenmaggie are expected to exceed the minor flood level during Wednesday at downstream of Lake Glenmaggie.

Macalister River downstream of Lake Glenmaggie:

Minor flooding is likely along the Macalister River downstream of Lake Glenmaggie.The Macalister River downstream of Lake Glenmaggie is currently at 2.14 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. 

The Macalister River downstream of Lake Glenmaggie is likely to exceed the minor flood level (2.60 m) during Wednesday due to increases in planned releases from Lake Glenmaggie.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • The Macalister River in flood will cause the low lying farmland areas around, Tinamba, Newry, Heyfield, Maffra and Desailly to become inundated.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home may occur in some locations.
 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 04/10/2023 at 3:00pm or as the situation changes.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point includes Whorouly to Wangaratta .

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE ALONG THE OVENS RIVER DURING WEDNESDAY 
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE ALONG THE KING RIVER 
 
  • Minor flooding is possible at several locations along the Ovens River. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at downstream of Lake William Hovell and Cheshunt. 
  • Moderate flooding is possible along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge 

  • In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Wednesday, up to 100 mm of rainfall has been recorded across the Ovens and King River catchments with isolated totals of up to 165 mm recorded in the upper catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for the next few days. 
  • This situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point includes Whorouly to Wangaratta
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 9.15 m and rising slowly.
  • An update on the flood prediction for Wangaratta will be provided with the next  Bureau of Meteorology update after 3pm this afternoon.
Ovens River to Bright: 
  • Minor flooding may occur along the Ovens River to Bright. The Ovens River at Bright is currently at 2.68 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Bright may exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) Wednesday morning, with further rises possible. 
Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point: 
  • Minor flooding may occur along the Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point. The Ovens River at Eurobin is currently at 4.06 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Eurobin may exceed the minor flood level (4.50 m) Wednesday late morning or early afternoon, with further rises possible. 
  • The Ovens River at Rocky Point is currently at 2.80 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Rocky Point may exceed the minor flood level (3.20 m) Wednesday late morning or early afternoon, with further rises possible
Buckland River: 
  • Strong river level rises are occurring along the Buckland River, minor flooding may develop later Wednesday morning. 
Buffalo River: 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Buffalo River. The Buffalo River downstream of Lake Buffalo is currently at 5.00 metres and steady. The Buffalo River downstream of  Lake Buffalo is likely to remain around the moderate flood level (5.00 m) during Wednesday. 
King River: 
  • Moderate flooding may occur along the King River. The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is currently at 2.12 metres and rising, above the minor flood level. The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is likely to remain above the minor flood level (1.80 m) during Wednesday. 
  • The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 2.99 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge may exceed the minor flood level (3.70 m) Wednesday late morning or early afternoon. The river level may exceed the moderate flood level (3.95 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday. 
Fifteen Mile Creek: 
  • Minor flooding may occur along the Fifteen Mile Creek. The Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South is currently at 2.40 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South may reach the minor flood level (2.80 m) Wednesday late morning or early afternoon, with further rises possible.   
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock, pumps and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • For information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
In Whorouly
  • At Minor flood level in Whorouly, no homes are likely to be affected. Low lying sheds close to waterways may be flooded.
In Wangaratta:
  • Shallow flooding into park area around Templeton Street boat ramp - road remains above flood level but walking tracks closed 
  • Water against Painters Island river levee / concrete path over most of its length 
  • Shallow flooding (backwater flooding) into backyards and to rear fences around a few homes in Templeton St and the railway bridge  
  • Likely closure of Great Alpine Road at Yellow Creek, travel via the Detour Road bypass. 
  • Paths from Sydney Beaches to the the Stockbridge footbridge closed 
  • Bike Paths and walkways along the One and Three Miles Creeks within Wangaratta township closed due to flooding.
  • Carparks along the Ovens River likely to be closed.

At 11.9 m the Minor flood level in Wangaratta,
  • Possible overtopping of Hoban Street beneath the rail line - may cut access to 1 house 
  • Ovens River commences flooding over the river bank at Apex Park and Painters Island Caravan Park.  
  • Water up to Yogi’s Chin in APEX Park 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream.
  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 89mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 34mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Tuesday 03 October 2023. 
  • Rainfall totals of 5-10 mm is forecast for the catchment for Wednesday 04 October 2023.
  • Water levels of the Yarra River and Watts Rivers at various locations are rising in response to the rain.
Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:
  • The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently at 3.56 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres). It is expected to peak above the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres) overnight.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is expected to cause substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to be impacted by floodwaters.
